# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: expectation-maximization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistics, an **expectation–maximization** (**EM**) **algorithm** is an iterative method to find (local) maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates of parameters in statistical models, where the model depends on unobserved latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] These parameter-estimates are then used to determine the distribution of the latent variables in the next E step.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It can be used, for example, to estimate a mixture of gaussians, or to solve the multiple linear regression problem.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm was explained and given its name in a classic 1977 paper by Arthur Dempster, Nan Laird, and Donald Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] They pointed out that the method had been "proposed many times in special circumstances" by earlier authors.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One of the earliest is the gene-counting method for estimating allele frequencies by Cedric Smith.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley in 1958, and Hartley and Hocking in 1977, from which many of the ideas in the Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper originated.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Another one by S.K Ng, Thriyambakam Krishnan and G.J McLachlan in 1977.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley's ideas can be broadened to any grouped discrete distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A very detailed treatment of the EM method for exponential families was published by Rolf Sundberg in his thesis and several papers, following his collaboration with Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper in 1977 generalized the method and sketched a convergence analysis for a wider class of problems.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper established the EM method as an important tool of statistical analysis.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence analysis of the Dempster–Laird–Rubin algorithm was flawed and a correct convergence analysis was published by C.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Wu's proof established the EM method's convergence also outside of the exponential family, as claimed by Dempster–Laird–Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm is used to find (local) maximum likelihood parameters of a statistical model in cases where the equations cannot be solved directly.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Typically these models involve latent variables in addition to unknown parameters and known data observations.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] That is, either missing values exist among the data, or the model can be formulated more simply by assuming the existence of further unobserved data points.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, a mixture model can be described more simply by assuming that each observed data point has a corresponding unobserved data point, or latent variable, specifying the mixture component to which each data point belongs.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Finding a maximum likelihood solution typically requires taking the derivatives of the likelihood function with respect to all the unknown values, the parameters and the latent variables, and simultaneously solving the resulting equations.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistical models with latent variables, this is usually impossible.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Instead, the result is typically a set of interlocking equations in which the solution to the parameters requires the values of the latent variables and vice versa, but substituting one set of equations into the other produces an unsolvable equation.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm proceeds from the observation that there is a way to solve these two sets of equations numerically.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One can simply pick arbitrary values for one of the two sets of unknowns, use them to estimate the second set, then use these new values to find a better estimate of the first set, and then keep alternating between the two until the resulting values both converge to fixed points.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It's not obvious that this will work, but it can be proven in this context.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Additionally, it can be proven that the derivative of the likelihood is (arbitrarily close to) zero at that point, which in turn means that the point is either a local maximum or a saddle point.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In general, multiple maxima may occur, with no guarantee that the global maximum will be found.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Some likelihoods also have singularities in them, i.e., nonsensical maxima.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, one of the *solutions* that may be found by EM in a mixture model involves setting one of the components to have zero variance and the mean parameter for the same component to be equal to one of the data points.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, this quantity is often intractable since $\mathbf {Z}$ is unobserved and the distribution of $\mathbf {Z}$ is unknown before attaining ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The missing values (aka latent variables) $\mathbf {Z}$ are discrete, drawn from a fixed number of values, and with one latent variable per observed unit.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The parameters are continuous, and are of two kinds: Parameters that are associated with all data points, and those associated with a specific value of a latent variable (i.e., associated with all data points whose corresponding latent variable has that value).
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, it is possible to apply EM to other sorts of models.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Compute the probability of each possible value of ⁠ $\mathbf {Z}$ ⁠, given ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, use the just-computed values of $\mathbf {Z}$ to compute a better estimate for the parameters ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Iterate steps 2 and 3 until convergence.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The algorithm as just described monotonically approaches a local minimum of the cost function.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Although an EM iteration does increase the observed data (i.e., marginal) likelihood function, no guarantee exists that the sequence converges to a maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For multimodal distributions, this means that an EM algorithm may converge to a local maximum of the observed data likelihood function, depending on starting values.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A variety of heuristic or metaheuristic approaches exist to escape a local maximum, such as random-restart hill climbing (starting with several different random initial estimates ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)}$ ⁠), or applying simulated annealing methods.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is especially useful when the likelihood is an exponential family, see Sundberg (2019, Ch.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] 8) for a comprehensive treatment: the E step becomes the sum of expectations of sufficient statistics, and the M step involves maximizing a linear function.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In such a case, it is usually possible to derive closed-form expression updates for each step, using the Sundberg formula (proved and published by Rolf Sundberg, based on unpublished results of Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf).
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM method was modified to compute maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates for Bayesian inference in the original paper by Dempster, Laird, and Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Other methods exist to find maximum likelihood estimates, such as gradient descent, conjugate gradient, or variants of the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Unlike EM, such methods typically require the evaluation of first and/or second derivatives of the likelihood function.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Expectation-Maximization works to improve $Q({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)})$ rather than directly improving $\log p(\mathbf {X} \mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Here it is shown that improvements to the former imply improvements to the latter.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm can be viewed as two alternating maximization steps, that is, as an example of coordinate descent.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Consider the function: $F(q,\theta ):=\operatorname {E} _{q}[\log L(\theta ;x,Z)]+H(q),$ where q is an arbitrary probability distribution over the unobserved data z and *H*(*q*) is the entropy of the distribution q.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A Kalman filter is typically used for on-line state estimation and a minimum-variance smoother may be employed for off-line or batch state estimation.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, these minimum-variance solutions require estimates of the state-space model parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM algorithms can be used for solving joint state and parameter estimation problems.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Operate a Kalman filter or a minimum-variance smoother designed with current parameter estimates to obtain updated state estimates.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Use the filtered or smoothed state estimates within maximum-likelihood calculations to obtain updated parameter estimates.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Suppose that a Kalman filter or minimum-variance smoother operates on measurements of a single-input-single-output system that possess additive white noise.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ are scalar output estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother from N scalar measurements $z_{k}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The above update can also be applied to updating a Poisson measurement noise intensity.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ and ${\widehat {x}}_{k+1}$ are scalar state estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence of parameter estimates such as those above are well studied.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A number of methods have been proposed to accelerate the sometimes slow convergence of the EM algorithm, such as those using conjugate gradient and modified Newton's methods (Newton–Raphson).
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Also, EM can be used with constrained estimation methods.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This idea is further extended in *generalized expectation maximization (GEM)* algorithm, in which is sought only an increase in the objective function F for both the E step and M step as described in the As a maximization–maximization procedure section.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] GEM is further developed in a distributed environment and shows promising results.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is also possible to consider the EM algorithm as a subclass of the **MM** (Majorize/Minimize or Minorize/Maximize, depending on context) algorithm, and therefore use any machinery developed in the more general case.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Q-function used in the EM algorithm is based on the log likelihood.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Therefore, it is regarded as the log-EM algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The use of the log likelihood can be generalized to that of the α-log likelihood ratio.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, the α-log likelihood ratio of the observed data can be exactly expressed as equality by using the Q-function of the α-log likelihood ratio and the α-divergence.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Obtaining this Q-function is a generalized E step.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its maximization is a generalized M step.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This pair is called the α-EM algorithm which contains the log-EM algorithm as its subclass.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Thus, the α-EM algorithm by Yasuo Matsuyama is an exact generalization of the log-EM algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] No computation of gradient or Hessian matrix is needed.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM shows faster convergence than the log-EM algorithm by choosing an appropriate α.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM algorithm leads to a faster version of the Hidden Markov model estimation algorithm α-HMM.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is a partially non-Bayesian, maximum likelihood method.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its final result gives a probability distribution over the latent variables (in the Bayesian style) together with a point estimate for θ (either a maximum likelihood estimate or a posterior mode).
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A fully Bayesian version of this may be wanted, giving a probability distribution over θ and the latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Bayesian approach to inference is simply to treat θ as another latent variable.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In this paradigm, the distinction between the E and M steps disappears.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] If using the factorized Q approximation as described above (variational Bayes), solving can iterate over each latent variable (now including θ) and optimize them one at a time.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Now, k steps per iteration are needed, where k is the number of latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For graphical models this is easy to do as each variable's new Q depends only on its Markov blanket, so local message passing can be used for efficient inference.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In information geometry, the E step and the M step are interpreted as projections under dual affine connections, called the e-connection and the m-connection; the Kullback–Leibler divergence can also be understood in these terms.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where $\mathbb {I}$ is an indicator function and f is the probability density function of a multivariate normal.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In the last equality, for each i, one indicator $\mathbb {I} (z_{i}=j)$ is equal to zero, and one indicator is equal to one.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] These are called the "membership probabilities", which are normally considered the output of the E step (although this is not the Q function of below).
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Everything in the E step is known before the step is taken except $T_{j,i}$ , which is computed according to the equation at the beginning of the E step section.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This full conditional expectation does not need to be calculated in one step, because τ and ***μ***/**Σ** appear in separate linear terms and can thus be maximized independently.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] $Q(\theta \mid \theta ^{(t)})$ being quadratic in form means that determining the maximizing values of $\theta$ is relatively straightforward.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Also, $\tau$ , $({\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{1},\Sigma _{1})$ and $({\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{2},\Sigma _{2})$ may all be maximized independently since they all appear in separate linear terms.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Conclude the iterative process if the expectation update is sufficiently small.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The algorithm illustrated above can be generalized for mixtures of more than two multivariate normal distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm has been implemented in the case where an underlying linear regression model exists explaining the variation of some quantity, but where the values actually observed are censored or truncated versions of those represented in the model.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Special cases of this model include censored or truncated observations from one normal distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM typically converges to a local optimum, not necessarily the global optimum, with no bound on the convergence rate in general.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is possible that it can be arbitrarily poor in high dimensions and there can be an exponential number of local optima.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hence, a need exists for alternative methods for guaranteed learning, especially in the high-dimensional setting.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Alternatives to EM exist with better guarantees for consistency, which are termed *moment-based approaches* or the so-called *spectral techniques*.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Moment-based approaches to learning the parameters of a probabilistic model enjoy guarantees such as global convergence under certain conditions unlike EM which is often plagued by the issue of getting stuck in local optima.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Algorithms with guarantees for learning can be derived for a number of important models such as mixture models, HMMs etc.
[src:expectation-maximization/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For these spectral methods, no spurious local optima occur, and the true parameters can be consistently estimated under some regularity conditions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In statistics, a **mixture model** is a probabilistic model for representing the presence of subpopulations within an overall population, without requiring that an observed data set should identify the sub-population to which an individual observation belongs.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Formally a mixture model corresponds to the mixture distribution that represents the probability distribution of observations in the overall population.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are used for clustering, under the name model-based clustering, and also for density estimation.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models should not be confused with models for compositional data, i.e., data whose components are constrained to sum to a constant value (1, 100%, etc.).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] However, compositional models can be thought of as mixture models, where members of the population are sampled at random.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Conversely, mixture models can be thought of as compositional models, where the total size reading population has been normalized to 1.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In addition, in a Bayesian setting, the mixture weights and parameters will themselves be random variables, and prior distributions will be placed over the variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In such a case, the weights are typically viewed as a *K*-dimensional random vector drawn from a Dirichlet distribution (the conjugate prior of the categorical distribution), and the parameters will be distributed according to their respective conjugate priors.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This characterization uses *F* and *H* to describe arbitrary distributions over observations and parameters, respectively.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Typically *H* will be the conjugate prior of *F*.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The two most common choices of *F* are Gaussian aka "normal" (for real-valued observations) and categorical (for discrete observations).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A Bayesian Gaussian mixture model is commonly extended to fit a vector of unknown parameters (denoted in bold), or multivariate normal distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] To incorporate this prior into a Bayesian estimation, the prior is multiplied with the known distribution $p({\boldsymbol {x|\theta }})$ of the data ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ conditioned on the parameters ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ to be estimated.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Although EM-based parameter updates are well-established, providing the initial estimates for these parameters is currently an area of active research.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that this formulation yields a closed-form solution to the complete posterior distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimations of the random variable ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ may be obtained via one of several estimators, such as the mean or maximum of the posterior distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Such distributions are useful for assuming patch-wise shapes of images and clusters, for example.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In the case of image representation, each Gaussian may be tilted, expanded, and warped according to the covariance matrices ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}_{i}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] One Gaussian distribution of the set is fit to each patch (usually of size 8×8 pixels) in the image.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Notably, any distribution of points around a cluster (see *k*-means) may be accurately given enough Gaussian components, but scarcely over *K*=20 components are needed to accurately model a given image distribution or cluster of data.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Financial returns often behave differently in normal situations and during crisis times.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A mixture model for return data seems reasonable.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Sometimes the model used is a jump-diffusion model, or as a mixture of two normal distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] See Financial economics § Challenges and criticism and Financial risk management § Banking for further context.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that we observe the prices of *N* different houses.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Different types of houses in different neighborhoods will have vastly different prices, but the price of a particular type of house in a particular neighborhood (e.g., three-bedroom house in moderately upscale neighborhood) will tend to cluster fairly closely around the mean.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Fitting this model to observed prices, e.g., using the expectation-maximization algorithm, would tend to cluster the prices according to house type/neighborhood and reveal the spread of prices in each type/neighborhood.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that a document is composed of *N* different words from a total vocabulary of size *V*, where each word corresponds to one of *K* possible topics.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The distribution of such words could be modelled as a mixture of *K* different *V*-dimensional categorical distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A model of this sort is commonly termed a topic model.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that expectation maximization applied to such a model will typically fail to produce realistic results, due (among other things) to the excessive number of parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sorts of additional assumptions are typically necessary to get good results.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sort of additional constraint is placed over the topic identities of words, to take advantage of natural clustering.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The following example is based on an example in Christopher M.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Bishop, *Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning*.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Imagine that we are given an *N*×*N* black-and-white image that is known to be a scan of a hand-written digit between 0 and 9, but we don't know which digit is written.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] We can create a mixture model with $K=10$ different components, where each component is a vector of size $N^{2}$ of Bernoulli distributions (one per pixel).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Such a model can be trained with the expectation-maximization algorithm on an unlabeled set of hand-written digits, and will effectively cluster the images according to the digit being written.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The same model could then be used to recognize the digit of another image simply by holding the parameters constant, computing the probability of the new image for each possible digit (a trivial calculation), and returning the digit that generated the highest probability.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models apply in the problem of directing multiple projectiles at a target (as in air, land, or sea defense applications), where the physical and/or statistical characteristics of the projectiles differ within the multiple projectiles.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] An example might be shots from multiple munitions types or shots from multiple locations directed at one target.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The combination of projectile types may be characterized as a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Further, a well-known measure of accuracy for a group of projectiles is the circular error probable (CEP), which is the number *R* such that, on average, half of the group of projectiles falls within the circle of radius *R* about the target point.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model can be used to determine (or estimate) the value *R*.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model properly captures the different types of projectiles.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The financial example above is one direct application of the mixture model, a situation in which we assume an underlying mechanism so that each observation belongs to one of some number of different sources or categories.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This underlying mechanism may or may not, however, be observable.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In this form of mixture, each of the sources is described by a component probability density function, and its mixture weight is the probability that an observation comes from this component.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In an indirect application of the mixture model we do not assume such a mechanism.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model is simply used for its mathematical flexibilities.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, a mixture of two normal distributions with different means may result in a density with two modes, which is not modeled by standard parametric distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Another example is given by the possibility of mixture distributions to model fatter tails than the basic Gaussian ones, so as to be a candidate for modeling more extreme events.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model-based clustering is also predominantly used in identifying the state of the machine in predictive maintenance.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Density plots are used to analyze the density of high dimensional features.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] If multi-model densities are observed, then it is assumed that a finite set of densities are formed by a finite set of normal mixtures.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A multivariate Gaussian mixture model is used to cluster the feature data into k number of groups where k represents each state of the machine.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The machine state can be a normal state, power off state, or faulty state.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Each formed cluster can be diagnosed using techniques such as spectral analysis.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In the recent years, this has also been widely used in other areas such as early fault detection.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In image processing and computer vision, traditional image segmentation models often assign to one pixel only one exclusive pattern.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In fuzzy or soft segmentation, any pattern can have certain "ownership" over any single pixel.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] If the patterns are Gaussian, fuzzy segmentation naturally results in Gaussian mixtures.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Combined with other analytic or geometric tools (e.g., phase transitions over diffusive boundaries), such spatially regularized mixture models could lead to more realistic and computationally efficient segmentation methods.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Probabilistic mixture models such as Gaussian mixture models (GMM) are used to resolve point set registration problems in image processing and computer vision fields.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] For pair-wise point set registration, one point set is regarded as the centroids of mixture models, and the other point set is regarded as data points (observations).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] State-of-the-art methods are e.g. coherent point drift (CPD) and Student's t-distribution mixture models (TMM).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are widely used in the social sciences to cluster observational data and identify latent group structure in complex, heterogeneous populations.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In studies of armed conflict, unsupervised mixture-model-based clustering has been applied to conflict event data to group observations into empirically derived conflict types without relying on predefined categories.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Such analyses reveal systematic differences across clusters in geographic, demographic, economic and infrastructural characteristics, corresponding to distinct conflict archetypes associated with different population and development profiles.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This is one of the numerous examples of how mixture models can support data-driven classification in social science research.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Identifiability refers to the existence of a unique characterization for any one of the models in the class (family) being considered.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimation procedures may not be well-defined and asymptotic theory may not hold if a model is not identifiable.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Let *J* be the class of all binomial distributions with *n* = 2.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Clearly, given *p*0 and *p*1, it is not possible to determine the above mixture model uniquely, as there are three parameters (*π*, *θ*1, *θ*2) to be determined.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Consider a mixture of parametric distributions of the same class.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] be the class of all component distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Parametric mixture models are often used when we know the distribution *Y* and we can sample from *X*, but we would like to determine the *ai* and *θi* values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Such situations can arise in studies in which we sample from a population that is composed of several distinct subpopulations.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] It is common to think of probability mixture modeling as a missing data problem.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] One way to understand this is to assume that the data points under consideration have "membership" in one of the distributions we are using to model the data.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] When we start, this membership is unknown, or missing.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The job of estimation is to devise appropriate parameters for the model functions we choose, with the connection to the data points being represented as their membership in the individual model distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A variety of approaches to the problem of mixture decomposition have been proposed, many of which focus on maximum likelihood methods such as expectation maximization (EM) or maximum *a posteriori* estimation (MAP).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Generally these methods consider separately the questions of system identification and parameter estimation; methods to determine the number and functional form of components within a mixture are distinguished from methods to estimate the corresponding parameter values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Some notable departures are the graphical methods as outlined in Tarter and Lock and more recently minimum message length (MML) techniques such as Figueiredo and Jain and to some extent the moment matching pattern analysis routines suggested by McWilliam and Loh (2009).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Expectation maximization (EM) is seemingly the most popular technique used to determine the parameters of a mixture with an *a priori* given number of components.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a particular way of implementing maximum likelihood estimation for this problem.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Thus on the basis of the current estimate for the parameters, the conditional probability for a given observation *x*(*t*) being generated from state *s* is determined for each *t* = 1, …, *N* ; *N* being the sample size.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The parameters are then updated such that the new component weights correspond to the average conditional probability and each component mean and covariance is the component specific weighted average of the mean and covariance of the entire sample.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Dempster also showed that each successive EM iteration will not decrease the likelihood, a property not shared by other gradient based maximization techniques.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, EM naturally embeds within it constraints on the probability vector, and for sufficiently large sample sizes positive definiteness of the covariance iterates.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a key advantage since explicitly constrained methods incur extra computational costs to check and maintain appropriate values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Theoretically EM is a first-order algorithm and as such converges slowly to a fixed-point solution.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Redner and Walker (1984) make this point arguing in favour of superlinear and second order Newton and quasi-Newton methods and reporting slow convergence in EM on the basis of their empirical tests.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] They do concede that convergence in likelihood was rapid even if convergence in the parameter values themselves was not.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The relative merits of EM and other algorithms vis-à-vis convergence have been discussed in other literature.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Other common objections to the use of EM are that it has a propensity to spuriously identify local maxima, as well as displaying sensitivity to initial values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Figueiredo and Jain note that convergence to 'meaningless' parameter values obtained at the boundary (where regularity conditions breakdown, e.g., Ghosh and Sen (1985)) is frequently observed when the number of model components exceeds the optimal/true one.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] On this basis they suggest a unified approach to estimation and identification in which the initial *n* is chosen to greatly exceed the expected optimal value.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Their optimization routine is constructed via a minimum message length (MML) criterion that effectively eliminates a candidate component if there is insufficient information to support it.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way it is possible to systematize reductions in *n* and consider estimation and identification jointly.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] With initial guesses for the parameters of our mixture model, "partial membership" of each data point in each constituent distribution is computed by calculating expectation values for the membership variables of each data point.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] With expectation values in hand for group membership, plug-in estimates are recomputed for the distribution parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixing coefficients *ai* are the means of the membership values over the *N* data points.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The component model parameters *θi* are also calculated by expectation maximization using data points *xj* that have been weighted using the membership values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] With new estimates for *ai* and the *θi'*s, the expectation step is repeated to recompute new membership values.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The entire procedure is repeated until model parameters converge.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] As an alternative to the EM algorithm, the mixture model parameters can be deduced using posterior sampling as indicated by Bayes' theorem.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] This is still regarded as an incomplete data problem in which membership of data points is the missing data.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A two-step iterative procedure known as Gibbs sampling can be used.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The previous example of a mixture of two Gaussian distributions can demonstrate how the method works.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] As before, initial guesses of the parameters for the mixture model are made.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Instead of computing partial memberships for each elemental distribution, a membership value for each data point is drawn from a Bernoulli distribution (that is, it will be assigned to either the first or the second Gaussian).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The Bernoulli parameter *θ* is determined for each data point on the basis of one of the constituent distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Draws from the distribution generate membership associations for each data point.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Plug-in estimators can then be used as in the M step of EM to generate a new set of mixture model parameters, and the binomial draw step repeated.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The method of moment matching is one of the oldest techniques for determining the mixture parameters dating back to Karl Pearson's seminal work of 1894.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In this approach the parameters of the mixture are determined such that the composite distribution has moments matching some given value.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In many instances extraction of solutions to the moment equations may present non-trivial algebraic or computational problems.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, numerical analysis by Day has indicated that such methods may be inefficient compared to EM.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Nonetheless, there has been renewed interest in this method, e.g., Craigmile and Titterington (1998) and Wang.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] McWilliam and Loh (2009) consider the characterisation of a hyper-cuboid normal mixture copula in large dimensional systems for which EM would be computationally prohibitive.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Here a pattern analysis routine is used to generate multivariate tail-dependencies consistent with a set of univariate and (in some sense) bivariate moments.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The performance of this method is then evaluated using equity log-return data with Kolmogorov–Smirnov test statistics suggesting a good descriptive fit.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Some problems in mixture model estimation can be solved using spectral methods.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In particular it becomes useful if data points *xi* are points in high-dimensional real space, and the hidden distributions are known to be log-concave (such as Gaussian distribution or Exponential distribution).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Spectral methods of learning mixture models are based on the use of Singular Value Decomposition of a matrix which contains data points.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The idea is to consider the top *k* singular vectors, where *k* is the number of distributions to be learned.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The projection of each data point to a linear subspace spanned by those vectors groups points originating from the same distribution very close together, while points from different distributions stay far apart.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] One distinctive feature of the spectral method is that it allows us to prove that if distributions satisfy certain separation condition (e.g., not too close), then the estimated mixture will be very close to the true one with high probability.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Tarter and Lock describe a graphical approach to mixture identification in which a kernel function is applied to an empirical frequency plot so to reduce intra-component variance.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way one may more readily identify components having differing means.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] While this *λ*-method does not require prior knowledge of the number or functional form of the components its success does rely on the choice of the kernel parameters which to some extent implicitly embeds assumptions about the component structure.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Some of them can even probably learn mixtures of heavy-tailed distributions including those with infinite variance (see links to papers below).
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In this setting, EM based methods would not work, since the Expectation step would diverge due to presence of outliers.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] For each *i*, generate *mi* random numbers from the *F**i* distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] In a Bayesian setting, additional levels can be added to the graphical model defining the mixture model.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, in the common latent Dirichlet allocation topic model, the observations are sets of words drawn from *D* different documents and the *K* mixture components represent topics that are shared across documents.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Each document has a different set of mixture weights, which specify the topics prevalent in that document.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] All sets of mixture weights share common hyperparameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] A very common extension is to connect the latent variables defining the mixture component identities into a Markov chain, instead of assuming that they are independent identically distributed random variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The resulting model is termed a hidden Markov model and is one of the most common sequential hierarchical models.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Numerous extensions of hidden Markov models have been developed; see the resulting article for more information.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] The motivation for this work was provided by the zoologist Walter Frank Raphael Weldon who had speculated in 1893 (in Tarter and Lock) that asymmetry in the histogram of these ratios could signal evolutionary divergence.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Pearson's approach was to fit a univariate mixture of two normals to the data by choosing the five parameters of the mixture such that the empirical moments matched that of the model.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] While his work was successful in identifying two potentially distinct sub-populations and in demonstrating the flexibility of mixtures as a moment matching tool, the formulation required the solution of a 9th degree (nonic) polynomial which at the time posed a significant computational challenge.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Subsequent works focused on addressing these problems, but it was not until the advent of the modern computer and the popularisation of Maximum Likelihood (MLE) parameterisation techniques that research really took off.
[src:expectation-maximization/gaussian-mixture-model] Since that time there has been a vast body of research on the subject spanning areas such as fisheries research, agriculture, botany, economics, medicine, genetics, psychology, palaeontology, electrophoresis, finance, geology and zoology.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In mathematics, **Jensen's inequality**, named after the Danish mathematician Johan Jensen, relates the value of a convex function of an integral to the integral of the convex function.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] It was proved by Jensen in 1906, building on an earlier proof of the same inequality for doubly-differentiable functions by Otto Hölder in 1889.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Given its generality, the inequality appears in many forms depending on the context, some of which are presented below.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In its simplest form the inequality states that the convex transformation of a mean is less than or equal to the mean applied after convex transformation (or equivalently, the opposite inequality for concave transformations).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The difference between the two sides of the inequality, $\operatorname {E} \left[\varphi (X)\right]-\varphi \left(\operatorname {E} [X]\right)$ , is called the Jensen gap.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The classical form of Jensen's inequality involves several numbers and weights.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The inequality can be stated quite generally using either the language of measure theory or (equivalently) probability.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In the probabilistic setting, the inequality can be further generalized to its *full strength*.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] A common application has x as a function of another variable (or set of variables) t, that is, $x_{i}=g(t_{i})$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] All of this carries directly over to the general continuous case: the weights *ai* are replaced by a non-negative integrable function *f* (*x*), such as a probability distribution, and the summations are replaced by integrals.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let $(\Omega ,A,\mu )$ be a probability space.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let $f:\Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ be a $\mu$ -integrable function and $\varphi :\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ be convex.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] where $a,b\in \mathbb {R}$ , and $f\colon [a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ is a non-negative Lebesgue-integrable function.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In this case, the Lebesgue measure of $[a,b]$ need not be 1.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] However, by integration by substitution, the interval can be rescaled so that it has measure 1.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The same result can be equivalently stated in a probability theory setting, by a simple change of notation.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let $(\Omega ,{\mathfrak {F}},\operatorname {P} )$ be a probability space, *X* an integrable real-valued random variable and $\varphi$ a convex function.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In this probability setting, the measure μ is intended as a probability $\operatorname {P}$ , the integral with respect to μ as an expected value $\operatorname {E}$ , and the function f as a random variable *X*.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Note that the equality holds if and only if $\varphi$ is a linear function on some convex set A such that $P(X\in A)=1$ (which follows by inspecting the measure-theoretical proof below).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] More generally, let *T* be a real topological vector space, and *X* a *T*-valued integrable random variable.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In this general setting, *integrable* means that there exists an element $\operatorname {E} [X]$ in *T*, such that for any element *z* in the dual space of *T*: $\operatorname {E} |\langle z,X\rangle |<\infty$ , and $\langle z,\operatorname {E} [X]\rangle =\operatorname {E} [\langle z,X\rangle ]$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Here $\operatorname {E} [\cdot \mid {\mathfrak {G}}]$ stands for the expectation conditioned to the σ-algebra ${\mathfrak {G}}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] This general statement reduces to the previous ones when the topological vector space T is the real axis, and ${\mathfrak {G}}$ is the trivial σ-algebra {∅, Ω} (where ∅ is the empty set, and Ω is the sample space).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let *X* be a one-dimensional random variable with mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma ^{2}\geq 0$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In particular, when $\varphi (x)$ is convex, then $\varphi ''(x)\geq 0$ , and the standard form of Jensen's inequality immediately follows for the case where $\varphi (x)$ is additionally assumed to be twice differentiable.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Jensen's inequality can be proved in several ways, and three different proofs corresponding to the different statements above will be offered.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Before embarking on these mathematical derivations, however, it is worth analyzing an intuitive graphical argument based on the probabilistic case where X is a real number (see figure).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Assuming a hypothetical distribution of X values, one can immediately identify the position of $\operatorname {E} [X]$ and its image $\varphi (\operatorname {E} [X])$ in the graph.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Consequently, in this picture the expectation of Y will always shift upwards with respect to the position of $\varphi (\operatorname {E} [X])$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] A similar reasoning holds if the distribution of X covers a decreasing portion of the convex function, or both a decreasing and an increasing portion of it.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] with equality when *φ*(*X*) is not strictly convex, e.g. when it is a straight line, or when X follows a degenerate distribution (i.e. is a constant).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The proofs below formalize this intuitive notion.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The *finite form* of the Jensen's inequality can be proved by induction: by convexity hypotheses, the statement is true for *n* = 2.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] We deduce the inequality is true for *n* + 1, by induction it follows that the result is also true for all integer *n* greater than 2.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In order to obtain the general inequality from this finite form, one needs to use a density argument.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Since convex functions are continuous, and since convex combinations of Dirac deltas are weakly dense in the set of probability measures (as could be easily verified), the general statement is obtained simply by a limiting procedure.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let g be a real-valued $\mu$ -integrable function on a probability space $\Omega$ , and let $\varphi$ be a convex function on the real numbers.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Since $\varphi$ is convex, at each real number x we have a nonempty set of subderivatives, which may be thought of as lines touching the graph of $\varphi$ at x , but which are below the graph of $\varphi$ at all points (support lines of the graph).
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Let *X* be an integrable random variable that takes values in a real topological vector space *T*.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In probabilistic language, *f* is a probability density function.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] This is applied in Variational Bayesian methods.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] In particular, if some even moment *2n* of *X* is finite, *X* has a finite mean.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] An extension of this argument shows *X* has finite moments of every order $l\in \mathbb {N}$ dividing *n*.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] There is also an infinite discrete form.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] where the expected values are with respect to some probability distribution in the random variable X.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] It shows that the average message length is minimised when codes are assigned on the basis of the true probabilities *p* rather than any other distribution *q*.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] The quantity that is non-negative is called the Kullback–Leibler divergence of *q* from *p*, where $D(p(x)\|q(x))=\int p(x)\log \left({\frac {p(x)}{q(x)}}\right)dx$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Since −log(*x*) is a strictly convex function for *x* > 0, it follows that equality holds when *p*(*x*) equals *q*(*x*) almost everywhere.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] the expected value of δ with respect to θ, taken over all possible vectors of observations *X* compatible with the same value of *T*(*X*) as that observed.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Further, because T is a sufficient statistic, $\delta _{1}(X)$ does not depend on θ, hence, becomes a statistic.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] This result is known as the Rao–Blackwell theorem.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] But this is simply Jensen's inequality for a *concave* $u(x)$ : a utility function that exhibits declining marginal utility.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Beyond its classical formulation for real numbers and convex functions, Jensen's inequality has been extended to the realm of operator theory.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] for every pair of self‐adjoint operators x and y (with spectra in I) and every scalar $\lambda \in [0,1]$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Hansen and Pedersen established a definitive version of this inequality by considering genuine non‐commutative convex combinations.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] This result shows that the convex transformation “respects” non-commutative convex combinations, thereby extending the classical inequality to operators without the need for additional restrictions on the interval of definition.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] A closely related extension is given by the Jensen trace inequality.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] This inequality naturally extends to C*-algebras equipped with a finite trace and is particularly useful in applications ranging from quantum statistical mechanics to information theory.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Furthermore, contractive versions of these operator inequalities are available when one only assumes $\sum _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{t}a_{i}\leq I$ , provided that additional conditions such as $f(0)\leq 0$ (when 0 ∈ I) are imposed.
[src:expectation-maximization/jensen-s-inequality] Extensions to continuous fields of operators and to settings involving conditional expectations on C-algebras further illustrate the broad applicability of these generalizations.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] In statistics, **latent variables** (from Latin: present participle of *lateo* 'lie hidden') are variables that can only be inferred indirectly through a mathematical model from other **observable variables** that can be directly observed or measured.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Latent variables may correspond to aspects of physical reality.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] These could in principle be measured, but may not be for practical reasons.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] In this situation, the term *hidden variables* is commonly used, reflecting the fact that the variables are meaningful, but not observable.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Other latent variables correspond to abstract concepts, like categories, behavioral or mental states, or data structures.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] The terms *hypothetical variables* or *hypothetical constructs* may be used in these situations.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] The use of latent variables can serve to reduce the dimensionality of data.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Many observable variables can be aggregated in a model to represent an underlying concept, making it easier to understand the data.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] In this sense, they serve a function similar to that of scientific theories.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] At the same time, latent variables link observable "sub-symbolic" data in the real world to symbolic data in the modeled world.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Latent variables, as created by factor analytic methods, generally represent "shared" variance, or the degree to which variables "move" together.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Variables that have no correlation cannot result in a latent construct based on the common factor model.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Examples of latent variables from the field of economics include quality of life, business confidence, morale, happiness and conservatism: these are all variables which cannot be measured directly.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] However, by linking these latent variables to other, observable variables, the values of the latent variables can be inferred from measurements of the observable variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Quality of life is a latent variable which cannot be measured directly, so observable variables are used to infer quality of life.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Observable variables to measure quality of life include wealth, employment, environment, physical and mental health, education, recreation and leisure time, and social belonging.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Latent-variable methodology is used in many branches of medicine.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] A class of problems that naturally lend themselves to latent variables approaches are longitudinal studies where the time scale (e.g. age of participant or time since study baseline) is not synchronized with the trait being studied.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] For such studies, an unobserved time scale that is synchronized with the trait being studied can be modeled as a transformation of the observed time scale using latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Examples of this include disease progression modeling and modeling of growth (see box).
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] There exists a range of different model classes and methodology that make use of latent variables and allow inference in the presence of latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/latent-variable] Bayesian statistics is often used for inferring latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In statistics, **maximum likelihood estimation** (**MLE**) is a method of estimating the parameters of an assumed probability distribution, given some observed data.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This is achieved by maximizing a likelihood function so that, under the assumed statistical model, the observed data is most probable.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The point in the parameter space that maximizes the likelihood function is called the maximum likelihood estimate.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The logic of maximum likelihood is both intuitive and flexible, and as such the method has become a dominant means of statistical inference.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If the likelihood function is differentiable, the derivative test for finding maxima can be applied.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In some cases, the first-order conditions of the likelihood function can be solved analytically; for instance, the ordinary least squares estimator for a linear regression model maximizes the likelihood when the random errors are assumed to have normal distributions with the same variance.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] From the perspective of Bayesian inference, MLE is generally equivalent to maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimation with a prior distribution that is uniform in the region of interest.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In frequentist inference, MLE is a special case of an extremum estimator, with the objective function being the likelihood.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] We model a set of observations as a random sample from an unknown joint probability distribution which is expressed in terms of a set of parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The goal of maximum likelihood estimation is to determine the parameters for which the observed data have the highest joint probability.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Evaluating the joint density at the observed data sample $\;\mathbf {y} =(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots ,y_{n})\;$ gives a real-valued function, ${\mathcal {L}}_{n}(\theta )={\mathcal {L}}_{n}(\theta ;\mathbf {y} )=f_{n}(\mathbf {y} ;\theta )\;,$ which is called the likelihood function.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Intuitively, this selects the parameter values that make the observed data most probable.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The specific value $~{\hat {\theta }}={\hat {\theta }}_{n}(\mathbf {y} )\in \Theta ~$ that maximizes the likelihood function $\,{\mathcal {L}}_{n}\,$ is called the maximum likelihood estimate.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Further, if the function $\;{\hat {\theta }}_{n}:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \Theta \;$ so defined is measurable, then it is called the maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is generally a function defined over the sample space, i.e. taking a given sample as its argument.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A sufficient but not necessary condition for its existence is for the likelihood function to be continuous over a parameter space $\,\Theta \,$ that is compact.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For an open $\,\Theta \,$ the likelihood function may increase without ever reaching a supremum value.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For some models, these equations can be explicitly solved for $\,{\widehat {\theta \,}}\,,$ but in general no closed-form solution to the maximization problem is known or available, and an MLE can only be found via numerical optimization.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Another problem is that in finite samples, there may exist multiple roots for the likelihood equations.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] is negative semi-definite at ${\widehat {\theta \,}}$ , as this indicates local concavity.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Conveniently, most common probability distributions – in particular the exponential family – are logarithmically concave.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] While the domain of the likelihood function—the parameter space—is generally a finite-dimensional subset of Euclidean space, additional restrictions sometimes need to be incorporated into the estimation process.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For instance, in a multivariate normal distribution the covariance matrix $\,\Sigma \,$ must be positive-definite; this restriction can be imposed by replacing $\;\Sigma =\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma \;,$ where $\Gamma$ is a real upper triangular matrix and $\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}$ is its transpose.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $~\lambda =\left[\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\ldots ,\lambda _{r}\right]^{\mathsf {T}}~$ is a column-vector of Lagrange multipliers and $\;{\frac {\partial h(\theta )^{\mathsf {T}}}{\partial \theta }}\;$ is the k × r Jacobian matrix of partial derivatives.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Naturally, if the constraints are not binding at the maximum, the Lagrange multipliers should be zero.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This in turn allows for a statistical test of the "validity" of the constraint, known as the Lagrange multiplier test.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Nonparametric maximum likelihood estimation can be performed using the empirical likelihood.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A maximum likelihood estimator is an extremum estimator obtained by maximizing, as a function of *θ*, the objective function ${\widehat {\ell \,}}(\theta \,;x)$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum-likelihood estimators have no optimum properties for finite samples, in the sense that (when evaluated on finite samples) other estimators may have greater concentration around the true parameter-value.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Under the conditions outlined below, the maximum likelihood estimator is consistent.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The consistency means that if the data were generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ and we have a sufficiently large number of observations *n*, then it is possible to find the value of *θ*0 with arbitrary precision.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In practical applications, data is never generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Rather, $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ is a model, often in idealized form, of the process generated by the data.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is a common aphorism in statistics that *all models are wrong*.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus, true consistency does not occur in practical applications.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Nevertheless, consistency is often considered to be a desirable property for an estimator to have.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] To establish consistency, the following conditions are sufficient.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness: the parameter space Θ of the model is compact.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The identification condition establishes that the log-likelihood has a unique global maximum.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness implies that the likelihood cannot approach the maximum value arbitrarily close at some other point (as demonstrated for example in the picture on the right).
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Compactness is only a sufficient condition and not a necessary condition.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Continuity: the function ln *f*(*x* | *θ*) is continuous in θ for almost all values of x: $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } {\Bigl [}\;\ln f(x\mid \theta )\;\in \;C^{0}(\Theta )\;{\Bigr ]}=1.$ The continuity here can be replaced with a slightly weaker condition of upper semi-continuity.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The dominance condition can be employed in the case of i.i.d. observations.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In the non-i.i.d. case, the uniform convergence in probability can be checked by showing that the sequence ${\widehat {\ell \,}}(\theta \mid x)$ is stochastically equicontinuous.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Additionally, if (as assumed above) the data were generated by $f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})$ , then under certain conditions, it can also be shown that the maximum likelihood estimator converges in distribution to a normal distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The maximum likelihood estimator selects the parameter value which gives the observed data the largest possible probability (or probability density, in the continuous case).
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If the parameter consists of a number of components, then we define their separate maximum likelihood estimators, as the corresponding component of the MLE of the complete parameter.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The MLE is also equivariant with respect to certain transformations of the data.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] and hence the likelihood functions for X and Y differ only by a factor that does not depend on the model parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For example, the MLE parameters of the log-normal distribution are the same as those of the normal distribution fitted to the logarithm of the data.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In fact, in the log-normal case if $X\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ , then $Y=g(X)=e^{X}$ follows a log-normal distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As assumed above, if the data were generated by $~f(\cdot \,;\theta _{0})~,$ then under certain conditions, it can also be shown that the maximum likelihood estimator converges in distribution to a normal distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is √*n* -consistent and asymptotically efficient, meaning that it reaches the Cramér–Rao bound.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In particular, it means that the bias of the maximum likelihood estimator is equal to zero up to the order ⁠1/√n ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, when we consider the higher-order terms in the expansion of the distribution of this estimator, it turns out that *θ*mle has bias of order 1⁄n.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This bias-corrected estimator is *second-order efficient* (at least within the curved exponential family), meaning that it has minimal mean squared error among all second-order bias-corrected estimators, up to the terms of the order ⁠1/ n2 ⁠ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It is possible to continue this process, that is to derive the third-order bias-correction term, and so on.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, the maximum likelihood estimator is *not* third-order efficient.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] A maximum likelihood estimator coincides with the most probable Bayesian estimator given a uniform prior distribution on the parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ is the prior distribution for the parameter θ and where $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})$ is the probability of the data averaged over all parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Since the denominator is independent of θ, the Bayesian estimator is obtained by maximizing $f(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}\mid \theta )\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ with respect to θ.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If we further assume that the prior $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ is a uniform distribution, the Bayesian estimator is obtained by maximizing the likelihood function $f(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}\mid \theta )$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus the Bayesian estimator coincides with the maximum likelihood estimator for a uniform prior distribution $\operatorname {\mathbb {P} } (\theta )$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In many practical applications in machine learning, maximum-likelihood estimation is used as the model for parameter estimation.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The Bayesian Decision theory is about designing a classifier that minimizes total expected risk, especially, when the costs (the loss function) associated with different decisions are equal, the classifier is minimizing the error over the whole distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum likelihood estimates of parameters can be substituted into expressions for the probability density function, cumulative distribution function, or quantile function, to generate predictions of probabilities or quantiles of out-of-sample events.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This method for predicting probabilities is recommended in statistics text-books and actuarial textbooks, and is widely used in the scientific literature.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] However, maximum likelihood prediction fails to propagate the uncertainty around the maximum likelihood parameter estimates into the prediction.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As a result, the predicted probabilities are not well calibrated, and should not be expected to correspond to the frequencies of out-of-sample events.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] In particular, tail exceedance probabilities and tail exceedance quantiles are typically underestimated, sometimes dramatically.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The underestimation is largest when there is little training data, many parameters being estimated, and for the far tail.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] For cases where this prediction bias is a problem, Bayesian predictions can provide a solution if the prior is chosen so as to reduce or eliminate the bias.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Consider a case where *n* tickets numbered from 1 to *n* are placed in a box and one is selected at random (*see uniform distribution*); thus, the sample size is 1.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] If *n* is unknown, then the maximum likelihood estimator ${\widehat {n}}$ of *n* is the number *m* on the drawn ticket.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] (The likelihood is 0 for *n* < *m*, 1⁄*n* for *n* ≥ *m*, and this is greatest when *n* = *m*.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] As a result, with a sample size of 1, the maximum likelihood estimator for *n* will systematically underestimate *n* by (*n* − 1)/2.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose one wishes to determine just how biased an unfair coin is.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Call the probability of tossing a 'head' *p*.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose the coin is tossed 80 times: i.e. the sample might be something like *x*1 = H, *x*2 = T, ..., *x*80 = T, and the count of the number of heads "H" is observed.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The probability of tossing tails is 1 − *p* (so here *p* is *θ* above).
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Suppose the outcome is 49 heads and 31 tails, and suppose the coin was taken from a box containing three coins: one which gives heads with probability *p* = 1⁄3, one which gives heads with probability *p* = 1⁄2 and another which gives heads with probability *p* = 2⁄3.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The coins have lost their labels, so which one it was is unknown.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Using maximum likelihood estimation, the coin that has the largest likelihood can be found, given the data that were observed.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The likelihood is maximized when p = 2⁄3, and so this is the *maximum likelihood estimate* for p.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Now suppose that there was only one coin but its p could have been any value 0 ≤ p ≤ 1 .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] and the maximisation is over all possible values 0 ≤ p ≤ 1 .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The solution that maximizes the likelihood is clearly p = 49⁄80 (since p = 0 and p = 1 result in a likelihood of 0).
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Thus the *maximum likelihood estimator* for p is 49⁄80.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This result is easily generalized by substituting a letter such as s in the place of 49 to represent the observed number of 'successes' of our Bernoulli trials, and a letter such as n in the place of 80 to represent the number of Bernoulli trials.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Exactly the same calculation yields s⁄n which is the maximum likelihood estimator for any sequence of n Bernoulli trials resulting in s 'successes'.
