[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximizing log likelihood, with and without constraints, can be an unsolvable problem in closed form, then we have to use iterative procedures.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] cannot be solved explicitly for an estimator ${\widehat {\theta }}={\widehat {\theta }}(\mathbf {y} )$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Instead, they need to be solved iteratively: starting from an initial guess of $\theta$ (say ${\widehat {\theta }}_{1}$ ), one seeks to obtain a convergent sequence $\left\{{\widehat {\theta }}_{r}\right\}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where the vector $\mathbf {d} _{r}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)$ indicates the descent direction of the *r*th "step," and the scalar $\eta _{r}$ captures the "step length," also known as the learning rate.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Gradient descent method requires to calculate the gradient at the *r*-th iteration, but no need to calculate the inverse of second-order derivative, i.e., the Hessian matrix.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Therefore, it is computationally faster than Newton–Raphson method.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] where $\mathbf {s} _{r}({\widehat {\theta }})$ is the score and $\mathbf {H} _{r}^{-1}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)$ is the inverse of the Hessian matrix of the log-likelihood function, both evaluated the *r*th iteration.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] But because the calculation of the Hessian matrix is computationally costly, numerous alternatives have been proposed.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Other quasi-Newton methods use more elaborate secant updates to give approximation of Hessian matrix.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] BFGS method is not guaranteed to converge unless the function has a quadratic Taylor expansion near an optimum.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Another popular method is to replace the Hessian with the Fisher information matrix, ${\mathcal {I}}(\theta )=\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } \left[\mathbf {H} _{r}\left({\widehat {\theta }}\right)\right]$ , giving us the Fisher scoring algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] This procedure is standard in the estimation of many methods, such as generalized linear models.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Although popular, quasi-Newton methods may converge to a stationary point that is not necessarily a local or global maximum, but rather a local minimum or a saddle point.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Therefore, it is important to assess the validity of the obtained solution to the likelihood equations, by verifying that the Hessian, evaluated at the solution, is both negative definite and well-conditioned.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Early users of maximum likelihood include Carl Friedrich Gauss, Pierre-Simon Laplace, Thorvald N.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] It was Ronald Fisher however, between 1912 and 1922, who single-handedly created the modern version of the method.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Maximum-likelihood estimation finally transcended heuristic justification in a proof published by Samuel S.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks in 1938, now called Wilks' theorem.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The theorem shows that the error in the logarithm of likelihood values for estimates from multiple independent observations is asymptotically *χ* 2-distributed, which enables convenient determination of a confidence region around any estimate of the parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] The only difficult part of Wilks' proof depends on the expected value of the Fisher information matrix, which is provided by a theorem proven by Fisher.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Wilks continued to improve on the generality of the theorem throughout his life, with his most general proof published in 1962.
[src:expectation-maximization/maximum-likelihood-estimation] Reviews of the development of maximum likelihood estimation have been provided by a number of authors.
